<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7087#p7087</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7087#p7087"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Basic n00b question about iNES/UNIF headers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7087#p7087"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Anonymous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />How did the real NES know how much PRG/CHR data to allocate to run the game properly?<br /></div><br /><br />The NES does not allocate any memory.  Only the 2k of RAM ($0000-07FF) and various areas of VRAM (CHR excluded) exists on the NES.  CHR-ROM, CHR-RAM, PRG, and SRAM all exist on the game cartridge... and it's all managed by cartridge hardware (PRG/CHR/SRAM are usually each on their own memory chip, for example).<br /><br />Unfortuntaly, ROM dumps can only contain software, not hardware... so it's up to headers to give the jist of how the hardware was layed out so the dumped software can be used appropriately.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=33">Disch</a> — Tue Nov 29, 2005 10:51 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
