<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2005-11-29T22:45:57-07:00</updated>
<published>2005-11-29T22:45:57-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7086#p7086</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7086#p7086"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Basic n00b question about iNES/UNIF headers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=7086#p7086"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />How did the real NES know how much PRG/CHR data to allocate to run the game properly? I assume that this is just hardwired info that is "undumpable", if you know what I mean?<br /></div><br /><br />Upper bits of bank select registers are ignored, so you get mirrors due to the modulo effect this has. If there are 4 PRG banks, selecting the fifth bank really selects the first one (100 AND 011 = 000). This is also how a dumper figures out how big the PRG and CHR are: keep selecting higher banks until the contents match earlier banks.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Tue Nov 29, 2005 10:45 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
