<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=6699#p6699</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=6699#p6699"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Basic n00b question about iNES/UNIF headers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=758&amp;p=6699#p6699"><![CDATA[
For normal carts, the most exotic chip would be a MAD-1, which seems to be a glorified demultiplexer like the LS138 and 139 chips it replaced.  It doesn't seem like a really difficult challenge to emulate.  <br /><br />So, it seems like SNES emulation really needs a systematic emulation of board types to make games work correctly.  A header would need to be added to the ROMs.  The real problem is the work involved in identifying the various boards and how they differ from each other.  As you can see with UNIF, it has taken years to adopt some of the standard and does not have the support to be a true replacement of the inferior iNES standard.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=58">Great Hierophant</a> — Thu Nov 17, 2005 9:16 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
